Biodun Oyebanji on Thurs­day was declared winner of Ekiti State governorship pri­mary of the All Progressives Congress. Oyebanji, the immediate past Secretary to Ekiti State Government, according to the chairman of the commit­tee for the primary election, Governor Mohammed Bada­ru of Jigawa State, polled 101,703 votes to defeat seven other contestants. The aspirants included Senator Opeyemi Bamidele, popularly called MOB, who polled 760 votes; former Min­ister of Works, Senator Dayo Adeyeye, garnered 691 votes, while former governorship aspirant, Kayode Ojo, got 767. Iteire Calls For More Checkpoints In Isoko North As Robbers… Tanker Explosion: Delta Will Take Steps To Avert Reoccurrence… A total number of 107,877 voters were accredited for the exercise out of which 104,983 voted. The seven aspirants had earlier called for the cancel­lation of the election prima­ry, alleging that the primary election committee are aides of Governor Kayode Fayemi, who were working to ensure that Oyebanji secured the par­ty’s ticket. But Ekiti chapter of the APC said the exercise would go on as scheduled, insisting that there was a level-playing field for all aspirants.